<p>3. Code Implementation &amp; Results</p>

<h2 id="1-recurrent-neural-network-overview">1. Recurrent Neural Network Overview</h2>

<p>Recurrent Neural Networks are a type of neural work designed for processing sequential data, such as text, audio, time-series data and more. As the name suggests, the key feature that makes RNNs unique is the presence of recursive computational loops that span adjacent time steps.</p>

<p>This recurrence enables RNN models to effectively maintain a persistent internal state or ‚Äúmemory‚Äù of prior inputs, which can inform the processing of data points later in the sequence.</p>

<p>You might recall that our basic neural network usually has at least an input layer, a hidden layer and an output layer. Here‚Äôs how the basic architecture of a RNN differs:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_1.png" height="auto" width="70%" />
</div>

<p>We can see that the RNN now introduces a recursive relationship somehow with $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$, and also introduces a dimension of time $t$ to its layers.</p>

<p>In the above diagram, the RNN structure consists of a single computational unit with the self-connected hidden state. However, we can actually ‚Äòunfold‚Äô this single computational unit to see how information cycles across timesteps:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_2.png" height="auto" width="75%" />
</div>

<p>As data passes through the RNN, we can see how the input sequence is processed across all time steps, and how the model is influenced by information from previous time steps.</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_3.png" height="auto" width="70%" />
</div>

<p>Hopefully it is also clear how each hidden unit $h^{&lt;\cdots&gt;}$ receives 2 inputs. For example, we see that $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$ receives two inputs colored in red, $h^{&lt;t-1&gt;}$ and $x^{&lt;t&gt;}$. Correspondingly, $h^{&lt;t+1&gt;}$ receives two inputs colored in purple, $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$ and $x^{&lt;t+1&gt;}$</p>

<p>You may also be wondering, how would a multi-layer RNN look like? It might be hard to imagine all the inputs and outputs moving about. It would look something like this:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_4.png" height="auto" width="70%" />
</div>

<p>There is also an important point to be made about <b>parameter sharing</b> in RNNs. Let‚Äôs say we have a classic feedforward neural network that is trained to predict the next character in English sentences (or text sequences). The feedforward net would require separate weights for each input-output mapping for every character position. Given two similar, but differently worded sentences:</p>

<ol>
  <li>‚ÄúToday, I went to the dentist‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúI went to the dentist today‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<p>The feedforward neural network would learn the contextual relationships completely independently, and thus relearn from scratch even if similar semantic patterns were seen before. It cannot develop a ‚Äòunified grammar model‚Äô.</p>

<p>On the otherhand, the RNN shares the weights across certain time-steps, so if it learns patterns or rules in one part of a sentence, these can be reapplied later even if the sequence order changes slightly. More technically, the RNN embeds language patterns as reusable transition functions in the shared weights, so they are retained and applied regardless of input sequence length, or sentence order.</p>

<p>This means that for sequential data (like characters in a sentence), using RNNs can result in simpler models with fewer parameters to train while having better performance compared to a classic feedforward neural network.</p>

<p>Okay, now we‚Äôre ready to learn how a RNN works under the hood. We‚Äôll proceed to describe the RNN operations mathematically.</p>

<h2 id="2-describing-the-rnn-mathematically">2. Describing the RNN mathematically</h2>

<p>In this section, we‚Äôll understand the operations happening within the RNN mathematically.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs begin by understanding what weight matrices get passed around in a single hidden layer RNN:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_5.png" height="auto" width="100%" />
</div>

<p>We can see that $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$ receives two weight matrices: $W_{hx}$ from $x$, and $W_{hh}$ from its past self.</p>

<p>Then, $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$ outputs a weight matrix $W_{yh}$ which is passed into $y^{&lt;t&gt;}$.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs unfold this to see things more clearly:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_6.png" height="auto" width="80%" />
</div>

<p>Now, we have a bigger picture of how the weight matrices are passed around the RNN. However, as we know, neural networks usually have other components like bias terms, and activation functions that add non-linearity. We‚Äôll understand the full picture of how these weight matrices are used to form the inputs to each node, in the next section.</p>

<h2 id="21-forward-propagation">2.1 Forward Propagation</h2>

<p>Let‚Äôs start by focusing on the inputs to the hidden layer node $h^{&lt;t&gt;}$, labelled in dark red:</p>

<div class="md-image-container">
    <img class="post-image" src="/assets/images/rnn_7.png" height="auto" width="80%" />
</div>

<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>¬†</mtext><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex"> ~ \\ </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span class="mspace nobreak">¬†</span></span><span class="mspace newline"></span></span></span></span></p>

<p>As mentioned, our RNN also has biases and activation functions. Here‚Äôs what the Net Input and Activation terms at node h look like:</p>

<p>$\text{Net Input to Node h:}$</p>

<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><menclose notation="box"><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="true"><mrow><msubsup><mi>z</mi><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&gt;</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>W</mi><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&gt;</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>W</mi><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>‚àí</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&gt;</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>h</mi></msub></mrow></mstyle></mstyle></mstyle></menclose></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex"> 
